one who made or sold arrows for bows. This surname has sometimes been confused with   Flesher  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Flesher","meanings":["English: occupational name for a butcher, from Middle English <i>fles(c)her</i>, <i>flesho(u)r</i> ‘butcher’, an agent derivative of <i>flesh</i> ‘meat’, or from Middle English <i>fleshheuer</i>, <i>fleshewer</i> ‘butcher’, a compound of <i>flesh</i> ‘meat’ + <i>heuer</i> ‘cutter’. This surname has sometimes been confused with   Fletcher  .","Americanized form of German   Fleischer  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ingleby","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places called Ingleby (in Lincolnshire, Yorkshire, and Derbyshire). The placenames mean ‘farmstead of the English’, from Old English <i>Engle</i> ‘English’ (genitive plural <i>Engla</i>) + Old Norse <i>bȳ</i> ‘farmstead’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When sir Robert ingleby Fletcher was born in 1030, his father, Richard Thurston Haldup, was 15 and his mother, Lady Hannah Marie de la Hay Fletcher, was 26. He had at least 2 sons with Avice Fitswarren. He died in 1100, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1030–1100":"1030–1100","1052–1085":"1052–1085","1075–1140":"1075–1140","1015–1074":"1015–1074","1004–1074":"1004–1074","1004":"1004","1015":"1015","1100":"1100","1075":"1075","1030":"1030","1074":"1074","1085":"1085","1140":"1140","1052":"1052","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"1030–1100":"1030–1100","1052–1085":"1052–1085","1075–1140":"1075–1140","1015–1074":"1015–1074","1004–1074":"1004–1074","1004":"1004","1015":"1015","1100":"1100","1075":"1075","1030":"1030","1074":"1074","1085":"1085","1140":"1140","1052":"1052","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","England":"England"},"fr":{"1030–1100":"1030–1100","1052–1085":"1052–1085","1075–1140":"1075–1140","1015–1074":"1015–1074","1004–1074":"1004–1074","1004":"1004","1015":"1015","1100":"1100","1075":"1075","1030":"1030","1074":"1074","1085":"1085","1140":"1140","1052":"1052","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque sir Robert ingleby Fletcher est né en 1030, son père, Richard Thurston Haldup, avait 15 ans et sa mère, Lady Hannah Marie de la Hay Fletcher, avait 26 ans. Il a eu au moins 2 fils avec Avice Fitswarren. Il est décédé en 1100, à l’âge de 70 ans."},"de":{"1030–1100":"1030–1100","1052–1085":"1052–1085","1075–1140":"1075–1140","1015–1074":"1015–1074","1004–1074":"1004–1074","1004":"1004","1015":"1015","1100":"1100","1075":"1075","1030":"1030","1074":"1074","1085":"1085","1140":"1140","1052":"1052","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","England":"England","lifeSummary":"Als sir Robert ingleby Fletcher 1030 geboren wurde, war sein Vater Richard Thurston Haldup 15 und seine Mutter Lady Hannah Marie de la Hay Fletcher 26. Er hatte mit Avice Fitswarren mindestens 2 Söhne. Er starb 1100 im Alter von 70 Jahren